40|$|The aim of {{this study}} was to {{investigate}} whether an extended course of <b>prophylactic</b> <b>antibiotic</b> could reduce the wound infection rate in a subtropical country. Fifty-three consecutive cases scheduled to receive major head and neck operations were randomised into one-day or three-day <b>prophylactic</b> <b>antibiotic</b> groups. Thirteen cases (24. 5 per cent) developed wound infections after operations. The duration of <b>prophylactic</b> <b>antibiotic</b> was not related to the surgical wound infection. However, pre-operative haemoglobulin less than 10. 5 g/dl (odds ratio: 7. 24, 95 per cent confidence interval: 1. 28 - 41. 0) and reconstruction with a free flap or pectoris major myocutaneous flap during the operation (odds ratio: 11. 04, 95 per cent confidence interval: 1. 17 - 104. 7) were associated factors significantly influencing post-operative wound infection. Therefore, one day of <b>prophylactic</b> <b>antibiotic</b> was effective in major head and neck procedures but should not be substituted for proper aseptic and meticulous surgical techniques...|$|R
